Pasternak: It=E2=80=99s a huge win. I really want to emphasize a point here=
, which is that lots of people love collecting young, emerging artists, but=
 Steve talks about really helping them and supporting them. He=E2=80=99s ta=
lking about not just buying their work, he actually hustles to help artists=
 out. When we were at Art Basel, he had recently fallen in love with a pain=
ter=E2=80=99s work from South Korea. He had books with him that he was givi=
ng to dealers to try to help her out because she didn=E2=80=99t have galler=
y representation. I don=E2=80=99t know many people who do what Steve does.

Uovo was opening a huge facility in Bushwick=E2=80=94and Steve knew that, o=
f course, there are more artists of all disciplines living in Brooklyn than=
 anywhere else in the world. He has often acquired work by those artists an=
d then shown it at Uovo. And then the fact that the
artists have a billboard in Bushwick=E2=80=94how many artists are going to =
have a giant mural anywhere, let alone in Bushwick, which is also a home to=
 so many artist=E2=80=99s studios? This is a real moment of pride for these=
 artists.

On an institutional level, what does the museum get out of identifying emer=
ging artists? You also have The Brooklyn Artists Exhibition this year for t=
he 200th anniversary of the museum, which also emphasized emerging artists.

Pasternak: Audiences today want to see artists of their time. Artists today=
 want to see artists of their time. And I think we approach it with a histo=
ric lens, because we=E2=80=99re trying to identify young, emerging=E2=80=94=
I should say, Brooklyn artists=E2=80=94who we think have important things t=
o say and who are adding to art history. That=E2=80=99s the job of the cura=
tors. That=E2=80=99s why we have the curators nominate artists that they=E2=
=80=99re keeping an eye on, whose studios they=E2=80=99re going to, and the=
n we take
a look together and decide whether we think they=E2=80=99re going to be abl=
e to pull off a really strong show. Though they may be young, we believe th=
at they=E2=80=99re going to be able to make a great mural. We think that th=
is is going to be really transformative for their practice. And we think th=
at their work is adding to the art-historical canon.

=E2=80=9CTo Stop People in Their Tracks=E2=80=9D

What=E2=80=99s the role of public art in all of this?

Pasternak: When Steve came up with this idea, I was thrilled because I used=
 to run a public arts organization in New York City called Creative Time. I=
 am a passionate believer in the role that art can play in the daily fabric=
 of the city=E2=80=94of any city. To stop people in their tracks, to have a=
 moment of beauty and wonder, and to think outside of whatever is in their =
news feed, on their phone, or what=E2=80=99s happening in their head about =
work or home, and to take them to another place, is a really beautiful and =
extraordinary thing that I don=E2=80=99t take for granted. So when Steve ha=
d mentioned this, it=E2=80=99s not like there=E2=80=99s a robust amount of =
public art happening in Bushwick, right? It tends to happen in Manhattan or=
 more resourced neighborhoods. As I said before, I really do want
opportunities just to engage with people out on the street. They may not be=
 people who go to galleries, they may not be people who think of themselves=
 as the art lovers who are going to museums, but this is a way for them to =
connect with people more broadly=E2=80=94and artists really want to do that=
