Guttman: One thing that I have never told Anne is that before I got involve=
d with the Brooklyn Museum, I had suggested this idea to another New York m=
useum, and I got turned down. It just shows Anne=E2=80=99s appreciation for=
 what this could mean to the community. Because I don=E2=80=99t think there=
=E2=80=99s any question, now that I look back at the five years we=E2=80=99=
ve been doing this, that this has had a big impact on the art community in =
Brooklyn, and maybe even all of New York.

Pasternak: It=E2=80=99s had an impact on the artists, themselves. Baseera K=
han ended up having a show at the Hirshhorn. Her career completely changed.=
 Museums started to buy her work. The same was true for John Edmonds. Many =
of the artists have had skyrocketing careers. John got hired by all these m=
ajor fashion magazines to do shoots. I mean, this was a guy
who didn=E2=80=99t have support before, so it was really game-changing for =
the artists involved.

How is the process run? How do you sift through what are obviously a large =
number of artists? I know that you have finalists=E2=80=94but you don=E2=80=
=99t announce them.

Pasternak: The curators come with a shortlist of about 25 or 30 artists, an=
d we take a look at them. Then we reach out to about three finalists who we=
 think would be really great for an exhibition, who are ready for an exhibi=
tion, as well as who can pull off a giant outdoor mural, and they=E2=80=99r=
e paid a proposal fee. We don=E2=80=99t make public who the finalists are b=
ecause we don=E2=80=99t want it to look like winners and losers out there. =
We just want to celebrate the winners.

Endnotes=E2=80=A6

The Wallpowers had a celebratory dinner at Acru ( https://www.acru.nyc/?utm=
_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F17%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+=
Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F10%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=
=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) on Saturday night, where a j=
unior Wallpower told me about the Morgan Library=E2=80=99s current ( https:=
//www.themorgan.org/exhibitions/belle-da-costa-greene?utm_campaign=3DWall+P=
ower+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F17%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBER=
S+%2812%2F10%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm=
_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) exhibition/tribute to its inaugural director, =
Belle da Costa Greene. So it was with great interest that I read the incomp=
arable Hilton Als=E2=80=99s essay=20
( https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2024/12/23/belle-da-costa-greene-art-r=
eview-morgan-library?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F17%2F2=
4%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F10%2F24%29&utm_medium=
=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) in=
 The New Yorker about Greene. =E2=80=9CI think this is the first major exhi=
bition I=E2=80=99ve seen that follows a kind of Jamesian trajectory, in whi=
ch the vagaries of life and art coexist and are subsumed by fiction and its=
 greater resonance,=E2=80=9D Als writes about Greene, who passed as Portugu=
ese with =E2=80=9CSpanish Cuban=E2=80=9D blood. In reality, Greene=E2=80=99=
s parents were Black. Of course, the most interesting thing about Greene is=
 that she was able to execute J.P. Morgan=E2=80=99s ambitions as a collecto=
r. =E2=80=9CMorgan had the money and the dream=E2=80=94and a great eye,=E2=
=80=9D Als writes, =E2=80=9Cbut Greene had the vision and creativity to see=
 that the library could tell a story, not so much about the accumulation of=
 stuff but about
man=E2=80=99s deep desire for
knowledge, and thus truth.=E2=80=9D

Read the essay. See the show. I=E2=80=99ll catch up with you again on Sunda=
y.

